{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"07661301-2fc5-4f9c-a936-39e95cd26714","content":"For a .NET Web API project, use the **`webapi`** template:\n\n```bash\ndotnet new webapi -n MyApi\n```\n\n### Authentication options (`--auth`):\n\n| Value | Description |\n|---|---|\n| `None` | No authentication (default) |\n| `IndividualB2C` | Azure AD B2C individual accounts |\n| `SingleOrg` | Single-tenant Azure AD |\n| `MultiOrg` | Multi-tenant Azure AD |\n| `Windows` | Windows authentication |\n\n### Example with auth:\n```bash\ndotnet new webapi --auth SingleOrg --domain mydomain.onmicrosoft.com\n```\n\nYou can also add JWT Bearer auth manually via `Microsoft.AspNetCore.Authentication.JwtBearer` if you need a custom identity provider. Want me to scaffold a project with a specific auth setup?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"889b1f62-86fa-40df-aae2-cfd1cd4ce14f","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about web API project templates and authentication options. This is a general knowledge question about .NET (likely, given the repository context with dotnet plugins). I can answer this from my knowledge without needing to search the codebase.","outputTokens":267,"requestId":"A804:3D936D:157A8A6:1804487:6A051DAE"},"id":"0149bad3-aa8c-4f3b-9b40-7bf4c776aab4","timestamp":"2026-05-14T00:56:21.897Z","parentId":"a9ecf723-02f1-4d1e-9f3a-a26a119fea77"}
